\section*{Question 12.35}
  \begin{Enumerate}
    \item $\alpha=0.10$.
    \item $H_{O}$:``The proportion of habitats used by the bear is the same as the proportions of available habitat'' versus $H_{A}$:``The proportion of habitats used by the bear is the same as the proportions of available habitat.''
    \item A goodness-of-fit test is required because a single categorical variable (habitat use) from a single population (this bear) was measured and the proportions are being compared to a theoretical distribution in the null hypothesis.
    \item This is an observational study with randomly selected times for observation.
    \item The expected number of observations in each habitat is in proportion to the GIS analysis of habitat availability.  Thus, the expected number in each habitat is shown in \tabref{tab:bear} (along with the observed frequencies).  Note that these percentages did not need to be adjusted to the number of observations because 100 observations were made.  The test statistic computed below should reasonably follow a $\chi^{2}$-distribution because all of the expected values are greater than five.
  \begin{table}[!h]
    \begin{center}
      \caption{Observed and expected frequencies for habitat use by a bear.}  \label{tab:bear}
        \begin{tabular}{ccc}
          \hline\hline
          & Obs & Exp \\
          Habitat & Freq & Freq \\
          \hline
          Lowland Conifer  & 47 & 34 \\
          Aspen            & 12 & 17 \\
          Open Areas       & 10 & 12 \\
          Upland Hardwoods & 21 & 25 \\
          Mixed Upland     & 10 & 12 \\
          \hline
          Total & 100 & 100 \\
          \hline\hline
        \end{tabular}
      \end{center}
    \end{table}
    \item The table of observed frequencies is shown in \tabref{tab:bear}.
    \item The $\chi^{2}$ test statistic is thus,
      \begin{center}
        \[  \begin{split}
          \chi^{2} &= \frac{(47-34)^{2}}{34} + \frac{(12-17)^{2}}{17} + \frac{(10-12)^{2}}{12} + \frac{(21-25)^{2}}{25}  + \frac{(10-12)^{2}}{12} \\
          &= 4.971 + 1.471 + 0.333 + 0.640 + 0.333 \\
          &= 7.7478 \\
        \end{split}  \]
      \end{center}
      with $5-1=4$ df.
    \item The p-value is \Sexpr{swvPvalue(distrib(7.7478,distrib="chisq",df=4,lower.tail=FALSE,plot=FALSE))}.
    \item The $H_{O}$ is not rejected because the $p-value>\alpha$.
    \item The bear appears to use the habitats in proportion to the availability of the habitat.
  \end{Enumerate}

